04944nam a22008295i 9781787441644DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874416447 a10.1515/97817874416442doi  a(DE-B1597)675745  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.01/11 aBandoch, Joshua, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of Place :bMontesquieu, Particularism, and the Pursuit of Liberty /cJoshua Bandoch.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2017] 1bUniversity of Rochester Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (266 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Montesquieu’s Political Science -- t2 Security, Liberty, and Prosperity as Particularistic Political Goals -- t3 The Political Variables -- t4 The Subpolitical Variables -- t5 The American Founding as a Particularistic Achievement -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA critical reexamination of Montesquieu's political science, revealing the primacy of place in the development of the best political order.Many Enlightenment thinkers sought to discover the right political order for all times and all places, and scholars often view Montesquieu as working within this project. In this reassessment of Montesquieu's political thought, Joshua Bandoch finds that Montesquieu broke from this ideal and, by taking into account the variation of societies, offered a more fruitful approach to the study of politics. Through a careful reading of Montesquieu's political writings, Bandoch shows that for Montesquieu the politics, economics, and morals of a society must fit a particular place and its people. As long as states commit to pursuing security, liberty, and prosperity, states can -- indeed, should -- define and advance these goals in their own particular ways. Montesquieu saw that the circumstances of a place -- its religion, commerce, laws, institutions, physical environment, and mores -- determine the best political order for that place. In this sense, Montesquieu is the great innovator of what Bandoch calls the "politics of place." This new reading of Montesquieu also provides fresh insights into the American founding, which Montesquieu so heavily influenced. Instead of having discerned the "right" political order, Bandoch argues, the Founders instituted a good political order, of which there are numerous versions. Joshua Bandoch earned his PhD in political science from the University of Notre Dame. He has taught at Brown University and the University of Wisconsin-Madison.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLibertyxPhilosophyxHistoryy18th century. 0aParticularism (Theology). 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophyxHistoryy18th century. 4aModern History. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAmerican Founding.  aAmerican founding.  aCultural Context.  aEnlightenment Thinkers.  aEnlightenment thinkers.  aGovernment.  aLiberty.  aMontesquieu.  aPolitical Order.  aPolitical Philosophy.  aPolitical Thought.  aPolitics of Place.  aSociety.  abest political order.  aeconomics.  aliberty.  amorals.  apolitical order.  apolitics of place.  apolitics.  aprosperity.  asecurity.  asociety.  avariation of societies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787441644?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787441644423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/co